¶ ⦊
  ‖ \ssection{Why} ⦉

  ‖ We can represent a probability distribution on a set of
    size $n$ by a vector in $𝗥^n$. ⦉
⦉

¶ ⦊
  ‖ \ssection{Definition} ⦉
⦉

¶ ⦊
  ‖ Let $A$ be a set with $\num{A} = n$ and let $p: A → 𝗥$
    be a probability distribution on $A$. ⦉

  ‖ For $σ: A → \N$ a numbering of $A$, define the vector
    $x_i = p(σ^{-1}{x})$. ⦉

  ‖ Then $x ≥ 0$ (elementwise) and $\transpose{1} x = 1$. ⦉
⦉

